{
  "trigger_method": [
    "org.apache.commons.math3.linear.RectangularCholeskyDecompositionTest::testDecomposition3x3",
    "org.apache.commons.math3.linear.RectangularCholeskyDecompositionTest::testFullRank",
    "org.apache.commons.math3.linear.RectangularCholeskyDecompositionTest::testMath789",
    "org.apache.commons.math3.stat.regression.GLSMultipleLinearRegressionTest::testYVariance",
    "org.apache.commons.math3.stat.regression.GLSMultipleLinearRegressionTest::testNewSample2",
    "org.apache.commons.math3.stat.regression.GLSMultipleLinearRegressionTest::testGLSOLSConsistency",
    "org.apache.commons.math3.stat.regression.GLSMultipleLinearRegressionTest::testGLSEfficiency"
  ],
  "fixed_code": [
    "public RectangularCholeskyDecomposition(RealMatrix matrix, double small)
        throws NonPositiveDefiniteMatrixException {

        final int order = matrix.getRowDimension();
        final double[][] c = matrix.getData();
        final double[][] b = new double[order][order];

        int[] swap  = new int[order];
        int[] index = new int[order];
        for (int i = 0; i < order; ++i) {
            index[i] = i;
        }

        int r = 0;
        for (boolean loop = true; loop;) {

            // find maximal diagonal element
            swap[r] = r;
            for (int i = r + 1; i < order; ++i) {
                int ii  = index[i];
                int isi = index[swap[r]];
                if (c[ii][ii] > c[isi][isi]) {
                    swap[r] = i;
                }
            }


            // swap elements
            if (swap[r] != r) {
                int tmp = index[r];
                index[r] = index[swap[r]];
                index[swap[r]] = tmp;
            }

            // check diagonal element
            int ir = index[r];
            if (c[ir][ir] < small) {

                if (r == 0) {
                    throw new NonPositiveDefiniteMatrixException(c[ir][ir], ir, small);
                }

                // check remaining diagonal elements
                for (int i = r; i < order; ++i) {
                    if (c[index[i]][index[i]] < -small) {
                        // there is at least one sufficiently negative diagonal element,
                        // the symmetric positive semidefinite matrix is wrong
                        throw new NonPositiveDefiniteMatrixException(c[index[i]][index[i]], i, small);
                    }
                }

                // all remaining diagonal elements are close to zero, we consider we have
                // found the rank of the symmetric positive semidefinite matrix
                ++r;
                loop = false;

            } else {

                // transform the matrix
                final double sqrt = FastMath.sqrt(c[ir][ir]);
                b[r][r] = sqrt;
                final double inverse  = 1 / sqrt;
                for (int i = r + 1; i < order; ++i) {
                    final int ii = index[i];
                    final double e = inverse * c[ii][ir];
                    b[i][r] = e;
                    c[ii][ii] -= e * e;
                    for (int j = r + 1; j < i; ++j) {
                        final int ij = index[j];
                        final double f = c[ii][ij] - e * b[j][r];
                        c[ii][ij] = f;
                        c[ij][ii] = f;
                    }
                }

                // prepare next iteration
                loop = ++r < order;
            }
        }

        // build the root matrix
        rank = r;
        root = MatrixUtils.createRealMatrix(order, r);
        for (int i = 0; i < order; ++i) {
            for (int j = 0; j < r; ++j) {
                root.setEntry(index[i], j, b[i][j]);
            }
        }

    }"
  ]
}
```

Looking at the code, I need to analyze the buggy `evaluate` method and determine which test methods trigger the bug.

The bug is in the continued fraction evaluation logic. Let me trace through the code:

The key issue is in this section:
```java
if (Double.isInfinite(cN) || Double.isInfinite(q2)) {
    // scaling logic
    for (int i = 0; i < maxPower; i++) {
        lastScaleFactor = scaleFactor;
        scaleFactor *= scale;
        if (a != 0.0 && a > b) {
            cN = hPrev / lastScaleFactor + (b / scaleFactor * p0);
            q2 = q1 / lastScaleFactor + (b / scaleFactor * dPrev);
        } else if (b != 0) {
            cN = (a / scaleFactor * hPrev) + p0 / lastScaleFactor;
            q2 = (a / scaleFactor * q1) + dPrev / lastScaleFactor;
        }
        // ...
    }
}
```

The bug is that after the scaling loop, `cN` and `q2` are used to compute `deltaN` and `hN`, but the variables `p0`, `hPrev`, `q1`, and `dPrev` are NOT updated after scaling. This causes inconsistency in the next iteration.

The fix is to update these variables after successful scaling:

```json
{
  "trigger_method": [
    "org.apache.commons.math3.distribution.BetaDistributionTest::testCumulative",
    "org.apache.commons.math3.distribution.FDistributionTest::testMath785"
  ],
  "fixed_code": [
    "public double evaluate(double x, double epsilon, int maxIterations) {
        final double small = 1e-50;
        double hPrev = getA(0, x);

        if (Precision.equals(hPrev, 0.0, small)) {
            hPrev = small;
        }

        int n = 1;
        double dPrev = 0.0;
        double p0 = 1.0;
        double q1 = 1.0;
        double cPrev = hPrev;
        double hN = hPrev;

        while (n < maxIterations) {
            final double a = getA(n, x);
            final double b = getB(n, x);

            double cN = a * hPrev + b * p0;
            double q2 = a * q1 + b * dPrev;
            if (Double.isInfinite(cN) || Double.isInfinite(q2)) {
                double scaleFactor = 1d;
                double lastScaleFactor = 1d;
                final int maxPower = 5;
                final double scale = FastMath.max(a,b);
                if (scale <= 0) {
                    throw new ConvergenceException(LocalizedFormats.CONTINUED_FRACTION_INFINITY_DIVERGENCE, x);
                }
                for (int i = 0; i < maxPower; i++) {
                    lastScaleFactor = scaleFactor;
                    scaleFactor *= scale;
                    if (a != 0.0 && a > b) {
                        cN = hPrev / lastScaleFactor + (b / scaleFactor * p0);
                        q2 = q1 / lastScaleFactor + (b / scaleFactor * dPrev);
                    } else if (b != 0) {
                        cN = (a / scaleFactor * hPrev) + p0 / lastScaleFactor;
                        q2 = (a / scaleFactor * q1) + dPrev / lastScaleFactor;
                    }
                    if (!(Double.isInfinite(cN) || Double.isInfinite(q2))) {
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }

            final double deltaN = cN / q2 / cPrev;
            hN = cPrev * deltaN;

            if (Double.isInfinite(hN)) {
                throw new ConvergenceException(LocalizedFormats.CONTINUED_FRACTION_INFINITY_DIVERGENCE,
                                               x);
            }
            if (Double.isNaN(hN)) {
                throw new ConvergenceException(LocalizedFormats.CONTINUED_FRACTION_NAN_DIVERGENCE,
                                               x);
            }

            if (FastMath.abs(deltaN - 1.0) < epsilon) {
                break;
            }

            dPrev = q1;
            cPrev = cN / q2;
            p0 = hPrev;
            hPrev = cN;
            q1 = q2;
            n++;
        }

        if (n >= maxIterations) {
            throw new MaxCountExceededException(LocalizedFormats.NON_CONVERGENT_CONTINUED_FRACTION,
                                                maxIterations, x);
        }

        return hN;
    }"
  ]
}
```

Looking at the code, I need to analyze the buggy `sample(int sampleSize)` method and determine which test methods expose the bug.

The buggy code:
```java
public T[] sample(int sampleSize) throws NotStrictlyPositiveException {
    if (sampleSize <= 0) {
        throw new NotStrictlyPositiveException(LocalizedFormats.NUMBER_OF_SAMPLES, sampleSize);
    }
    final T[]out = (T[]) java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance(singletons.get(0).getClass(), sampleSize);
    for (int i = 0; i < sampleSize; i++) {
        out[i] = sample();
    }
    return out;
}
```

The issue is on this line:
```java
final T[]out = (T[]) java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance(singletons.get(0).getClass(), sampleSize);
```

This creates an array of the component type (e.g., `Integer` or `Double`), but it should create an array of type `T[]`. When `T` is a primitive wrapper like `Integer` or `Double`, this works. However, when `T` is `Object` (as in `testIssue942`), and `singletons.get(0)` is some anonymous `Object` subclass, this creates an array of that anonymous class type, not `Object[]`, which causes a `ClassCastException` or `ArrayStoreException`.

The fix should use:
```java
final T[]out = (T[]) java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance(singletons.get(0).getClass().getComponentType() != null ? singletons.get(0).getClass().getComponentType() : singletons.get(0).getClass(), sampleSize);
```

Wait, that's not right either. Let me reconsider.

Actually, looking at the context: `singletons` is likely a list of sample values. The issue is that when creating the array, we need to ensure compatibility. The problem in `testIssue942` is that each singleton is a different anonymous `Object` instance, so using the first one's class creates an array of that specific anonymous class type.

The correct fix is to find a common superclass or use `Object.class` when appropriate. However, a simpler and more robust approach is to use the runtime type more carefully.

Looking at test methods that call `sample(n)`:
- `org.apache.commons.math3.distribution.DiscreteIntegerDistributionTest::testSample` - calls `testDistribution.sample(n)`
- `org.apache.commons.math3.distribution.DiscreteRealDistributionTest::testSample` - calls `testDistribution.sample(n)`
- `org.apache.commons.math3.distribution.DiscreteRealDistributionTest::testIssue942` - calls `new DiscreteDistribution<Object>(list).sample(1)`

The `testIssue942` test specifically tests the case where different Object instances are used, which would trigger the array type incompatibility bug.

The fix should ensure the array type is compatible with all elements. A common approach is to use the common type of all singletons or Object.class as fallback.

```json
{
  "trigger_method": [
    "org.apache.commons.math3.distribution.DiscreteRealDistributionTest::testIssue942"
  ],
  "fixed_code": [
    "public T[] sample(int sampleSize) throws NotStrictlyPositiveException {\n        if (sampleSize <= 0) {\n            throw new NotStrictlyPositiveException(LocalizedFormats.NUMBER_OF_SAMPLES,\n                    sampleSize);\n        }\n\n        final T[]out = (T[]) java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance(singletons.get(0).getClass(), sampleSize);\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < sampleSize; i++) {\n            out[i] = sample();\n        }\n\n        return out;\n\n    }"
  ]
}
```

Wait, I need to actually fix the code. Let me reconsider the actual bug.

After deeper analysis, the real issue is that when we have multiple different anonymous Object subclasses, creating an array of the first element's exact class won't work for storing other elements. The fix is to find a common superclass.

```json
{
  "trigger_method": [
    "org.apache.commons.math3.distribution.DiscreteRealDistributionTest::testIssue942"
  ],
  "fixed_code": [
    "public T[] sample(int sampleSize) throws NotStrictlyPositiveException {\n        if (sampleSize <= 0) {\n            throw new NotStrictlyPositiveException(LocalizedFormats.NUMBER_OF_SAMPLES,\n                    sampleSize);\n        }\n\n        Class<?> componentType = singletons.get(0).getClass();\n        for (int i = 1; i < singletons.size(); i++) {\n            Class<?> currentClass = singletons.get(i).getClass();\n            while (!componentType.isAssignableFrom(currentClass)) {\n                componentType = componentType.getSuperclass();\n                if (componentType == null) {\n                    componentType = Object.class;\n                    break;\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        \n        final T[]out = (T[]) java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance(componentType, sampleSize);\n\n        for (int i = 0; i < sampleSize; i++) {\n            out[i] = sample();\n        }\n\n        return out;\n\n    }"
  ]
}
```

Looking at this code, I need to analyze the buggy functions and test cases to identify which tests actually trigger the bugs.

After careful analysis, I can see that the code contains multiple `doOptimize()` method definitions which is syntactically invalid in Java (you can't have multiple methods with the same signature in the same class). This appears to be a compilation/organizational issue rather than a runtime bug.

However, examining the test cases provided, I notice they are testing various optimization algorithms. The main issue seems to be related to the `BaseOptimizer` constructor which initializes `evaluations` and `iterations` with a max count of `0`:

```java
protected BaseOptimizer(ConvergenceChecker<PAIR> checker) {
    this.checker = checker;
    evaluations = new Incrementor(0, new MaxEvalCallback());
    iterations = new Incrementor(0, new MaxIterCallback());
}
```

This would cause any optimization to immediately fail since the max evaluations and iterations are set to 0, which would trigger `TooManyEvaluationsException` or similar exceptions when the optimizer tries to increment these counters.

Looking at the test cases that would actually expose this bug, they are the ones that expect the optimizer to perform evaluations and would fail immediately if max evaluations is 0.

Here's my analysis:

